>, which is in most cases probably a variant of   Marriott   1.","variant of <b>Marritt</b>, itself a variant of   Merritt   2."]},{"name":"Maryott","meanings":["English: variant of   Marriott  ."]},{"name":"Merriott","meanings":["habitational name from Merriott in Somerset. The placename may derive from Old English <i>mere</i>, <i>miere</i> ‘mare’, <i>mere</i> ‘pool’, or <i>(ge)mǣre</i> ‘boundary’ + <i>geat</i> ‘gate, gap’.","from the Middle English male personal name <i>Meryet</i> (Old English <i>Mǣrgēat</i>, from <i>mǣre</i> ‘famous’ + <i>Gēat</i>, a tribal name). In post-medieval times, both this surname and the placename in 1 above underwent changes in pronunciation, sometimes by confusion with   Marriott  , and often by losing the medial <i>-i-</i> or <i>-y-</i>, hence   Merritt  ,   Meritt  , and so on.","English:"]},{"name":"Mary","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel, Myrtha, Pierre.","English: from the Middle English and Old French female personal name <i>Marie</i>, Latin   Maria  . Compare   Marrison  ,   Marion  ,   Marriott  ,   Markin  . — Note: It is likely that in the population figure published by the US Census Bureau (which dropped from 2215 in the year 2000 to 1547 in the year 2010) the female personal name <i>Mary</i> of some American bearers is also counted as a surname. Some of these bearers may be from countries, such as Indonesia, where (hereditary) surnames are not in general use; their personal name was thus registered as a surname only after their immigration to the US.","French: from a variant of the female personal name   Marie  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":15,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":46,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":71,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":84,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}